            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Shannon Riley wasn't born into the world she now sells. Her childhood was spent not in a Pacific Heights mansion, but in the foggy, working-class landscape of Daly City. The daughter of a union plumber and a school secretary, Shannon learned the value of a dollar and the power of grit early on. College was a distant dream; the immediate need was a paycheck. After graduating high school, she landed a job as a receptionist at a boutique real estate firm in San Francisco, drawn by the allure of the city she\u2019d always viewed from a distance.\n\nHer real education began there. While her peers were in lecture halls, Shannon was absorbing the art of the deal by osmosis. She learned the city not from a textbook, but by driving agents to showings\u2014from Sea Cliff\u2019s windswept estates to the sunny Victorians of Noe Valley. A turning point came when a senior broker, recognizing Shannon\u2019s sharp memory for details and preternatural ability to connect with people, took her under her wing. Shannon got her license at 22 and spent the next decade diligently building a client base. The 2008 market crash, which ruined many, solidified her career. While others panicked, she gave sober, steady advice, earning lifelong loyalty from clients who weathered the storm with her.\n\nNow 50, Shannon is a force in the luxury market. Her days are a blur of immaculate staging, high-stakes negotiations, and discreet client lunches. From her chic Marina condo, she drives her polished Audi A6 on the 5.5-mile commute to her downtown office, a queen in her meticulously crafted kingdom. Divorced for a decade, her most intimate relationships are often with her high-net-worth clients, for whom she is part therapist, part financial advisor.\n\nShannon\u2019s connection to San Francisco is deeply transactional, yet fiercely proprietary. She sells its dream, knowing intimately the hustle required to live it. Looking ahead, her ambition is shifting from closing deals to building a legacy. She dreams of mentoring a hungry, young agent\u2014someone like her former self\u2014and perhaps buying a small, quiet vineyard in Sonoma, a place where the value isn\u2019t calculated per square foot."
        },
