            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe remembers sitting in her father\u2019s Ford Ranger on a Daly City hill, watching the fog swallow all but the highest tips of San Francisco's skyline. He\u2019d point out towers he helped plumb. For her, it wasn\u2019t steel and glass; it was a distant, glittering kingdom she felt locked out of. That feeling of yearning, of being an outsider peering in, ignited a fierce resolve. It wasn't just a city; it was a destination, a future to be seized. (Around 16 years old)\n\n2.\nThe first time a senior agent tossed her the keys to his Jaguar. \"Move it to the front, would you?\" The weight of the key fob in her hand felt electric. Sliding into the driver's seat, the scent of expensive leather was intoxicating. It was more than a car; it was a portal. That brief moment made her ambition tangible, shifting her focus from simply getting by to attaining the very access and power that key represented. (Around 19 years old)\n\n3.\nEleanor, the firm\u2019s top broker, stopping her in the hall after a frantic meeting. \"That stat you recalled on the Presidio Terrace comp? That saved me.\" It wasn't praise for making coffee; it was acknowledgment of her intellect. For the first time, someone she admired saw past the receptionist and recognized the sharp, strategic mind beneath. That single sentence of validation gave her the final push of courage she needed to get her license. (Around 21 years old)\n\n4.\nThe phone call in late 2008. A young couple, weeping, certain they\u2019d lose the Noe Valley home she\u2019d just sold them. While other agents went dark, Shannon stayed on the line for an hour, her voice a steady anchor in their storm of panic. She didn't sell them anything; she gave them courage. In that moment of shared fear, she discovered her true value wasn't in the deal, but in the trust she could build when everything was falling apart. (Around 36 years old)\n\n5.\nLast week, standing on her Marina condo\u2019s balcony at dusk. The fog rolled in, obscuring the bridge, and she smiled, no longer feeling locked out by it. This view, this silence, was the spoils of a long war won. But the quiet also held a new question. The thrill of another closed deal felt distant, replaced by a deeper longing\u2014not for a bigger penthouse, but for a patch of earth in Sonoma. A place to grow something real. (Recently, age 50)"
